column66: Winter trips have great beach camping but require >2K cfs for motor in on C.  Summer June high-flow trips are exciting, but we cancel if combined flow is expected to exceed 50K cfs.  Our trips typically have one motor for three rafts, with two motors and 6 boats prefferred.  Rowing the lake is tough while staring at a dead motor.  Usuakky spend one night on river and one night at take-out.  Low lake levels make for better current to take-out.  Lack of camps below Dark canyon make motors essential.  Cataract is one of our (NM local) favorites with at least a June run planned every year.  My son Kyler Canyon Carpenter is named for Cataract experiences.

You did not ask about motorized vessels such as snout rigs, sport boats, j-rigs, s-rigs, etc but most commercial outfitters need these boats in order to navigate the river in the length of time people are willing to pay for trips. As a guide, my primary vessel is a J-Rig and I have seen the river from 3500cfs to 72,000cfs in this boat. There are different hazards to be wary of in a motorized craft that are not present in non-motorized (we have to watch our lower units, scuppers, frames, tubes, etc constantly!) This should be factored into your survey. All of my above answers are for my j-rig, not oar boat, as this is the craft I have the most experience in.

The key considerations at low water is wheth Tex's Riverways jet boat can navigate to pick up boaters from the confluence.  Without jet boat navigability, the ability to float a canoe to the confluence means nothing--you'd be stuck there without a jet boat pickup.
I would prefer to see as natural a flow as possible.  If natural peak is higher than 100,000, then that is fine.  If natural low flow is lower than 3000, then that is fine.

Your questioning is a bit vague, are we talking about just flatwater streches or about Cataract Canyon(as the link shows)  If we are talking about flows in Cataract, the Cisco gauge is not a good one to look at because it, does not figure in the flows from the Green River.  I answered the questions keeping in mind the flows in Cataract canyon (combination of the Cisco and Green River,UT gauges)  If we are only talking about the flatwater stretches, any flow is acceptable.

column66: How is this survey taking into account that the flows through Canyonlands National Park, specifically below the Confluence, are dependent upon not only the Colorado River but also the Green?  I'm concerned that since it is not specifically addressed that the survey information may be manipulated in irresponsible ways.  For example, the probability that flows on the Cisco gage hit 40,000 cfs on any given year are quite low, however, hitting 20,000 cfs, and assuming an approximately equal contribution from the Green, then Cataract Canyon would be running 40,000, which is not an unreasonable flow.  The survey doesn't seem to address this at all and that concerns me.
